<TITLE> Matin dismisses US findings on rights </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 13 (bdnews24.com)Home affairs adviser MA Matin has dismissed findings of the US State Department's report released Tuesday on the human rights situation in Bangladesh. "The state department cannot make such comments," the adviser told reporters Thursday after a monthly meeting on the law and order situation at the secretariat.e law and order situation at the secretariat. The US State Department's Country Report on Human Rights for 2007 said the human rights situation had worsened under emergency powers rules. It was also critical of the government's treatment of the two former prime ministers Sheikh Hasina and Khaleda Zia. "We have to consider the reality. We have treated them (the two former prime ministers) with due respect and proper care," Matin said. The report said the government had imposed unofficial house arrests of Sheikh Hasina and Khaleda Zia, and made repeated efforts in the first six months of the year to force them into exile. The home adviser said: "The government will comment on it after examining the report." On whether Hasina would be sent abroad the adviser said: "Sheikh Hasina was admitted to Square Hospital in accordance with her wishes. I spoke to her personally." "The government has to follow certain rules and regulations. She requires around twenty separate medical tests." "If the hospital authorities fail to provide her proper treatment the government will form a medical board." "If the board recommends she would be sent abroad. The government is compassionate in this regard," the home adviser said. bdnew
